{"title_page": "Ashutosh Kumar", "text_new": "'''Ashutosh Kumar''' is a Bihar born political activist. He is founder and national president of Bhumihar Brahman Ekta Manch Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashutoshkumarofficial.com/|title=Official website of Ashutosh Kumar}}</ref> Ashutosh established this organisation in June 2018 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.economictimes.com/company/bhumihar-brahman-ekta-manch-foundation-/U74999UP2018NPL105007/|title=About the organisation}}</ref> to unite Bhumihar and Brahman community together. Ashutosh led nationwide movement for reservation of economically weaker section of upper class <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashutoshkumarofficial.com/mission|title=Mission of Ashutosh Kumar}}</ref> under banner of Bhumihar Brahman Ekta Manch foundation. Ashutosh also called up complete Bihar Bandh against Sc-St Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://=zeenews.india.com/hindi/india/bihar-jharkhand/brahman-bhumihar-ekta-manch-protest-against-sc-st-act-in-bihar/440568/|title=Ashutosh Called Bihar Bandh against SC St act}}</ref> Recently in a historical rally in Gandhi Maidan Patna Ashutosh announced that he is going to launch political party before upcoming Bihar assembly election 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashutoshkumarofficial.com/political-journey|title=Political Journey of Ashutosh Kumar}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "'''Ashutosh Kumar''' is a Bihar born poltical activist. He is founder and national president of Bhumihar Brahman Ekta Manch Foundation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashutoshkumarofficial.com/|title=Official website of Ashutosh Kumar}}</ref> Ashutosh established this organisation in June 2018 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.economictimes.com/company/bhumihar-brahman-ekta-manch-foundation-/U74999UP2018NPL105007/|title=About the organisation}}</ref> to unite Bhumihar and Brahman community together. Ashutosh led nationwide movement for reservation of economically weaker section of upper class <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashutoshkumarofficial.com/mission|title=Mission of Ashutosh Kumar}}</ref> under banner of Bhumihar Brahman Ekta Manch foundation. Ashutosh also called up complete Bihar Bandh against Sc-St Act. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://=zeenews.india.com/hindi/india/bihar-jharkhand/brahman-bhumihar-ekta-manch-protest-against-sc-st-act-in-bihar/440568/|title=Ashutosh Called Bihar Bandh against SC St act}}</ref> Recently in a historical rally in Gandhi Maidan Patna Ashutosh announced that he is going to launch political party before upcoming Bihar assembly election 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashutoshkumarofficial.com/political-journey|title=Political Journey of Ashutosh Kumar}}</ref>\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtags,typo(s) fixed: poltical \u2192 political", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashutosh_Kumar"}
{"title_page": "Montserrat Caball\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Short description|Spanish operatic soprano}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Spanish name|Caball\u00e9|Folch}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Most Excellent|Excelent\u00edsima Se\u00f1ora]] [[Don (honorific)|Do\u00f1a]]\n| name               = Montserrat Caball\u00e9\n| alias              = La Superba\n| image              = Montserrat Caball\u00e9 1971b.jpg\n| caption            = Caball\u00e9 in [[Milan]], 1971\n| birth_name         = Mar\u00eda de Montserrat Viviana Concepci\u00f3n Caball\u00e9 i Folch\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1933|4|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Barcelona]], [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republic]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2018|10|6|1933|4|12}}\n| death_place        = Barcelona, [[Spain]]\n| education          = [[Conservatori Superior de M\u00fasica del Liceu]]\n| occupation         = Operatic [[soprano]]\n| years_active       = 1956\u20132018\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed]]|1964}}\n| children           = [[Montserrat Mart\u00ed]]<br>Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed Jr.\n| awards             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kammers\u00e4nger]]in\n* Honorary doctorate from the [[Universidad Internacional Men\u00e9ndez Pelayo]]\n* [[Princess of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award]]\n* [[Grammy Award]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mar\u00eda de Montserrat Viviana Concepci\u00f3n Caball\u00e9 i Folch''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|k|\u0259|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|l|j|e\u026a|,_|\u02cc|k|\u00e6|b|\u00e6|l|\u02c8|j|e\u026a}},<ref>{{Cite Oxford\u00a0Dictionaries|Caball\u00e9, Montserrat|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> {{IPA-ca|muns\u0259\u02c8rat k\u0259\u03b2\u0259\u02c8\u028ee i \u02c8folk|lang}}; 12 April 1933 \u2013 6 October 2018) was a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] [[operatic soprano]]. She sang a wide variety of roles, but is best known as an exponent of the works of [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]] and of the [[bel canto]] repertoire, notably the works of [[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini]], [[Vincenzo Bellini|Bellini]], and [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]]. She was noticed internationally when she stepped in for a performance of Donizetti's ''[[Lucrezia Borgia (opera)|Lucrezia Borgia]]'' at [[Carnegie Hall]] in 1965, and then appeared at leading opera houses. Her voice was described as pure but powerful, with superb control of vocal shadings and exquisite [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]].\n\nCaball\u00e9 became popular to non-classical music audiences in 1987, when she recorded, at the request of the [[International Olympic Committee|IOC]], \"[[Barcelona (Freddie Mercury and Montserrat Caball\u00e9 song)|Barcelona]]\", a duet with [[Freddie Mercury]], which became an official theme song for the [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic Games]]. She received several international awards and also [[Grammy Awards]] for a number of her recordings.\n\n==Early life and career==\nCaball\u00e9 was born in [[Barcelona]] on 12 April 1933.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Women in World History|last=Smith|first=Bonnie G.|authorlink=Bonnie G. Smith|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Her family was of humble financial circumstances due to the [[Spanish Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She studied music at the [[Liceu Conservatory]], and singing technique with Napoleone Annovazzi, Eugenia Kem\u00e9ny and [[Conchita Bad\u00eda]]. She graduated with a gold medal in 1954. She subsequently moved to [[Basel]], Switzerland, where she made her professional debut in 1956 as Mim\u00ec in Puccini's ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]''. She became part of the [[Theater Basel|Basel Opera]] company between 1957 and 1959, singing a repertoire that included Mozart (Erste Dame in ''[[The Magic Flute|Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'') and Strauss (''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'') in German, unusual for Spanish singers, but which proved useful for her next engagement at the [[Theater Bremen|Bremen Opera]] (1959\u20131962). In 1961, she starred as Iphig\u00e9nie in Gluck's ''[[Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride (Gluck)|Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride]]'' at the [[Teatro Nacional de S\u00e3o Carlos|National Theatre of S. Carlos]] in Lisbon, alongside [[Raymond Wolansky]], [[Jean Cox]], [[Paul Sch\u00f6ffler]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mt8XBGub1WsC&pg=PA308|title=The Grove Book of Operas|accessdate=6 October 2018|via=Google Books|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006155034/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mt8XBGub1WsC&pg=PA308|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, Caball\u00e9 returned to Barcelona and debuted at the [[Liceu]], singing the title role in Strauss's ''[[Arabella]]''. From the fall of 1962 through the spring of 1963 she toured Mexico, at one point singing the title role in Massenet's ''[[Manon]]'' at the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]]. This was followed by several more successful appearances at the [[Liceu]] in 1963.<ref name=\"oper\" />\n\n==International Success==\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9 1969cr.jpg|thumb|Caball\u00e9 in 1969]]\nCaball\u00e9's international breakthrough came in 1965 when she replaced an indisposed [[Marilyn Horne]] in a semi-staged performance of Donizetti's ''[[Lucrezia Borgia (opera)|Lucrezia Borgia]]'' at New York's [[Carnegie Hall]], which earned her a 25-minute standing ovation. While this was her first engagement in a bel canto opera and she had to learn the role in less than one month, her performance made her famous throughout the opera world. Later that year, Caball\u00e9 made her debut at the [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera|Glyndebourne Festival]] singing her first Marschallin in Richard Strauss' ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' and portraying the role of Countess Almaviva in Mozart's ''[[The Marriage of Figaro|Le nozze di Figaro]]''.<ref name=\"oper\">[http://hosting.operissimo.com/triboni/exec?method=com.operissimo.artist.webDisplay&id=ffcyoieagxaaaaabjjco&xsl=webDisplay&searchStr= Biography of Montserrat Caball\u00e9 at operissimo.com (in German)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327202713/http://hosting.operissimo.com/triboni/exec?method=com.operissimo.artist.webDisplay&id=ffcyoieagxaaaaabjjco&xsl=webDisplay&searchStr= |date=27 March 2012 }}. Hosting.operissimo.com. Retrieved 29 October 2015.</ref>\n\nIn December 1965, she returned to Carnegie Hall for her second bel canto opera, singing the role of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]] in Donizetti's recently rediscovered ''[[Roberto Devereux]]''. Caball\u00e9 closed out the year with her [[Metropolitan Opera]] debut on 22 December 1965, appearing as Marguerite in Gounod's ''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' alongside [[John Alexander (tenor)|John Alexander]] in the title role, [[Justino D\u00edaz]] as M\u00e9phistoph\u00e9l\u00e8s, and [[Sherrill Milnes]] as Valentin in his debut at the Met.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nIn 1966, Caball\u00e9 made her first appearance with the [[Philadelphia Lyric Opera Company]] as Maddalena di Coigny in Giordano's ''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]''<ref name=\"Phili\">[[Free Library of Philadelphia]]: ''Box: Phila. Lyric Opera Company: 782.1 P5326p Bal Two [1968 \u2013 1975]''</ref> and her Italian debut at the [[Maggio Musicale Fiorentino]] as Leonora in Verdi's ''[[Il trovatore]]'', followed by Bellini's ''[[Il pirata]]'' in 1967. She returned to Philadelphia in 1967 to sing the title roles in Puccini's ''[[Tosca]]'' and ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'',<ref name=\"Phili\" /> and to the Met to sing three Verdi heroines: Leonora alongside [[Richard Tucker]] as Manrico, Desdemona in ''[[Otello]]'' with [[James McCracken]] in the title role, and Violetta in ''[[La traviata]]'', with Tucker and [[George Shirley]] alternating as Alfredo.<ref name=\"Met\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/frame.htm|title=Metropolitan Opera Association|website=Archives.metoperafamily.org|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611003537/http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/frame.htm|archive-date=11 June 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The last role in particular garnered her further acclaim among American critics and audiences.<ref name=\"oper\" /> She returned to the Met the following year in the title role in Verdi's ''[[Luisa Miller]]'', and in 1969 for the role of Li\u00f9 in Puccini's ''[[Turandot]]'', with [[Birgit Nilsson]] in the title role and [[James King (tenor)|James King]] as Cal\u00e0f.<ref name=\"Met\" /> She also returned to Philadelphia as Imogene in Bellini's ''[[Il pirata]]'' (1968) and Lucrezia Borgia (1969).<ref name=\"Phili\" />\n\nIn 1969, Caball\u00e9 appeared at the [[Arena di Verona]] in a [[Jean Vilar]] production of Verdi's ''[[Don Carlos|Don Carlo]]''. She was Elisabetta of Valois in an all-star cast including [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] and [[Piero Cappuccilli]]. Her high B on the final \"ciel\" at the end of the opera lasted more than 20 bars up to the final chord from the orchestra. In these performances she had to act on crutches because of an accident earlier that year in New York City. In the same period she also appeared in recital at the Teatro Corallo in [[Verona]]. In 1970, Caball\u00e9 made her official debut at [[La Scala]] in the title role of ''Lucrezia Borgia''. She appeared as Leonora in Philadelphia,<ref name=\"Phili\" /> and returned to the Met as Amelia in a critically acclaimed production of Verdi's ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' with Domingo as Riccardo, and [[Reri Grist]] as Oscar.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nIn 1972, she made her first appearances at [[The Royal Opera|Covent Garden]] and the [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]], both in the role of Violetta.<ref name=\"oper\" /> That same year she returned to the Met as Elisabetta in ''Don Carlo'' with [[Franco Corelli]] in the title role, and sang the title role of Bellini's ''[[Norma (opera)|Norma]]'' in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Phili\" /> In 1973 she returned to Chicago to perform the title role in Donizetti's ''[[Maria Stuarda]]'' with [[Viorica Cortez]], appeared as Violetta in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Phili\" /> She performed at the Met as Bellini's Norma, opposite [[Carlo Cossutta]] in his Met debut as Pollione and [[Fiorenza Cossotto]] as Adalgisa.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9 1975.jpg|thumb|Caball\u00e9 in 1975]]\nIn 1974, Caball\u00e9 appeared in the title role of Verdi's ''[[Aida]]'' at the Liceu in January, in Verdi's ''[[I vespri siciliani]]'' at the Met in March,<ref name=\"Met\" /> and in ''[[Parisina (opera)|Parisina d'Este]]'' at Carnegie Hall, also in March. She appeared as Norma at the [[Bolshoi Theatre]] in Moscow and in ''Adriana Lecouvreur'' at La Scala in April. She was filmed as Norma in [[Orange, Vaucluse|Orange]] in July by Pierre Jourdain. She recorded ''Aida'' with [[Riccardo Muti]] in July and made a recording of duets with [[Giuseppe Di Stefano]] in August. In September 1974, she underwent major surgery to remove a large benign mass from her abdomen. She recovered and was performing again on stage by early 1975. In 1976 Caball\u00e9 appeared at the Met once again as Norma and sang her first Aida in that house, alongside [[Robert Nagy (tenor)|Robert Nagy]] as Radam\u00e8s and Marilyn Horne as Amneris. She appeared in the title role of ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'' by Richard Strauss and sang Mim\u00ec in Puccini's ''La boh\u00e8me'' with [[Luciano Pavarotti]] as Rodolfo.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nIn 1977 Caball\u00e9 made her debut with the [[San Francisco Opera]] in the title role of Puccini's ''Turandot''. She returned to that house ten more times over the next decade in such roles as Elvira in Verdi's ''[[Ernani]]'' and the title roles in Ponchielli's ''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'', Rossini's ''[[Semiramide]]'', and Puccini's ''Tosca'', among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007224557/http://archive.sfopera.com/qry3WebCastlist.asp?psearchall=on&psearch=Montserrat%20Caball%C3%A9&psearchtype |title=San Francisco Opera Performance Archive |website=Web.archive.org |date=2018-10-07 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nHaving lost some of her earlier brilliance and purity of voice, Caball\u00e9 offered more dramatic expressive singing in roles that demanded it. In 1978, she was Tosca in San Francisco with Pavarotti, Norma in Madrid, and Adriana Lecouvreur at the Met opposite [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]]. She continued to appear often at the Met during the 1980s, in roles such as Tosca (1980, 1985) and Elisabetta (1985), and also sang concerts in 1981 and 1983. Her final performance at the Met was on 10 October 1985 in ''Tosca'' with Pavarotti as Cavaradossi and [[Cornell MacNeil]] as Scarpia.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nHer voice was noted for its purity, precise control, and power. She was admired less for her dramatic instincts and acting skills than for her superb technique, vocal shadings, and exquisite [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]]s, which were inspired by [[Miguel Fleta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/03/09/134141700/montserrat-caball-a-voice-of-passionate-grandeur/|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9: A Voice of Passionate Grandeur|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154817/https://www.npr.org/2011/03/09/134141700/montserrat-caball-a-voice-of-passionate-grandeur/|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diarci.com/2012/10/12/perfectly-lovely-montserrat-caballe/|title=Perfectly Lovely \u2013 Montserrat Caballe|date=13 October 2012|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154759/http://www.diarci.com/2012/10/12/perfectly-lovely-montserrat-caballe/|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voiceteacher.com/cuperto.html|title=The Cuperto|website=voiceteacher.com|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206230329/http://www.voiceteacher.com/cuperto.html|archive-date=6 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://voiceandopera.blogspot.com/2011/08/those-caballe-pianissimi.html|title=Voice and opera training: Those Caballe pianissimi|first=Joel|last=Katz|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006114731/http://voiceandopera.blogspot.com/2011/08/those-caballe-pianissimi.html|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Assoluta Voice in Opera, 1797\u20131847|last=Riggs|first=Geoffrey S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GhXggJliLF8C|publisher=McFarland|year=2003|isbn=0786440775|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|pages=125, 127, 144|access-date=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006234813/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GhXggJliLF8C|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nIn Bellini's ''Norma'', Caball\u00e9 recorded both the title role (for [[RCA Red Seal Records|RCA Red Seal]] in 1972, with Domingo as Pollione) and later the role of Adalgisa, to [[Joan Sutherland]]'s Norma in a 1984 [[Decca Records|Decca]] recording conducted by [[Richard Bonynge]]. Although Bellini conceived the role of Adalgisa originally for a soprano, it is usually now sung by a [[mezzo-soprano]]. Caball\u00e9 was one of few sopranos to have recorded the role, although she was over 50 years old at the time of the recording in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w0qMf-bAx_QC&pg=PA11|title=Opera for Libraries: A Guide to Core Works, Audio and Video Recordings, Books and Serials|first=Clyde T.|last=McCants|date=28 February 2003|publisher=McFarland|accessdate=6 October 2018|via=Google Books|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006155047/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w0qMf-bAx_QC&pg=PA11|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1986 she also took a role in the biographic film ''[[Romanza final]]'', directed by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Forqu\u00e9]].\n\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9.jpg|thumb|left|upright|As Rossini's [[Semiramide]] at the 1980 [[Aix-en-Provence Festival]]]]\nIn 1987, Caball\u00e9 made a rare excursion into the world of pop music when she released a duet with [[Freddie Mercury]], the lead singer of the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], which was titled \"[[Barcelona (Freddie Mercury and Montserrat Caball\u00e9 song)|Barcelona]]\".<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9, Barcelona opera singer, dies at 85 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-45769808 |accessdate=6 October 2018 |publisher=BBC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006080359/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-45769808 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The song was inspired by Caball\u00e9's home city and later used as one of the two official theme songs for the [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"BBC\" /> Mercury was a great admirer of Caball\u00e9, considering her voice to be \"the best in the world\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/sep/27/freddie-mercury-great-enigma | title=Freddie Mercury: the great enigma | work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London | first=Caroline | last=Sullivan | date=27 September 2012 | accessdate=9 April 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609093810/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/sep/27/freddie-mercury-great-enigma | archive-date=9 June 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The single was followed by an [[Barcelona (Freddie Mercury and Montserrat Caball\u00e9 album)|album of the same name]] which was released the following year and featured further collaborations between the two performers. The title track later became the anthem of the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] which was hosted by Caball\u00e9's native city, and appeared again in the pop music charts throughout Europe. Caball\u00e9 also performed the song live, accompanied by a recording by Mercury, who had died in 1991, before the 1999 [[UEFA Champions League]] football final in Barcelona's [[Camp Nou]] stadium.<ref>{{cite journal |year=1999 |editor1-last=Mitten |editor1-first=Andy |title=The Long Road Trip to Victory |journal=Kings of Europe |publisher=Manchester United |page=11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pilger |first1=Sam |date=June 1999 |editor1-last=Barnes |editor1-first=Justyn |title=The Promised Land |journal=Manchester United |publisher=Manchester United |volume=7 |issue=8 |page=27 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, writing for ''[[The Independent]]'', Fiammetta Rocco said: \"Caballe is one of the last of the true divas. Callas is dead, [[Kiri Te Kanawa]] is busy making commercials for [[Sainsbury's]], and [[Mirella Freni]] has never really risen out of the narrow confines of being an opera lover's opera-singer. Caballe, on the other hand, has always had an enormous following, and it's still with her today.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/when-the-ample-catalan-sings-callas-is-no-more-kiri-te-kanawa-is-making-television-commercials-but-1437682.html|title=When the ample Catalan sings: Callas is no more; Kiri Te Kanawa is|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154930/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/when-the-ample-catalan-sings-callas-is-no-more-kiri-te-kanawa-is-making-television-commercials-but-1437682.html|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995 she worked with [[Vangelis]] for his album ''[[El Greco (album)|El Greco]]'', dedicated to [[El Greco|the Greek painter]].  In 1997, [[Mike Moran (music producer)|Mike Moran]] produced the album ''[[Friends for Life (Montserrat Caball\u00e9 album)|Friends For Life]]'', which includes duets with Caball\u00e9 and such singers as [[Bruce Dickinson]], [[Johnny Hallyday]], [[Johnny Logan (singer)|Johnny Logan]], [[Gino Vannelli]], and [[Helmut Lotti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/montserrat-caball%C3%A9-friends-for-life-mw0000451837/credits|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9: Friends for Life \u2013 Montserrat Caball\u00e9 \u2013 Credits|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194723/https://www.allmusic.com/album/montserrat-caball%C3%A9-friends-for-life-mw0000451837/credits|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCaball\u00e9 dedicated herself to various charities. She was a [[UNESCO Goodwill Ambassador]] and established a foundation for needy children in Barcelona. In 2003, she starred in her own documentary film ''Caball\u00e9: Beyond Music'', which featured many well-known opera singers, including Domingo, Pavarotti, Carreras, and [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operatoday.com/content/2005/04/caballe_beyond_.php |title=Caballe: Beyond Music |website=operatoday:com |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194622/http://www.operatoday.com/content/2005/04/caballe_beyond_.php |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, she appeared as Catherine of Aragon in ''[[Henry VIII (opera)|Henri VIII]]'' by Saint-Sa\u00ebns, and in 2004 in the title role of Massenet's ''[[Cl\u00e9op\u00e2tre]]'', both at the Liceu. She appeared as The Duchess of Crakenthorp in Donizetti's ''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' at the [[Vienna State Opera]] in April 2007.<ref name=\"Vienna\">{{cite web |url=https://archiv.wiener-staatsoper.at/search/person/455 |title=Vorstellungen mit Montserrat Caball\u00e9 |publisher=[[Vienna State Opera]] |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194739/https://archiv.wiener-staatsoper.at/search/person/455 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Patrick O'Connor wrote in ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'' that{{quote|no diva in memory has sung such an all-encompassing amount of the soprano repertory, progressing through virtually the entire range of Italian light lyric, [[Spinto|lirico-spinto]] and dramatic roles, including all the pinnacles of the bel canto, Verdi and verismo repertories, whilst simultaneously being a remarkable interpreter of Salome, Sieglinde and Isolde.<ref name=\"Gramophone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gramophone.co.uk/classical-music-news/the-soprano-montserrat-caball%C3%A9-has-died |title=The soprano Montserrat Caball\u00e9 has died |publisher=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]] |date=6 October 2018 |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006162041/https://www.gramophone.co.uk/classical-music-news/the-soprano-montserrat-caball%C3%A9-has-died |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nOn 6 June 2013, Caball\u00e9 was declared [[List of people declared personae non gratae in Azerbaijan|''persona non grata'' in Azerbaijan]] after visiting, despite official warnings issued by the Azerbaijani embassy in Spain, the de facto independent state [[Nagorno-Karabakh]] and meeting with local leaders.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/azerbaijan-montserrat-caballe/25009201.html Montserrat Caballe Declared Persona Non Grata In Azerbaijan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107083917/http://www.rferl.org/content/azerbaijan-montserrat-caballe/25009201.html |date=7 January 2016 }}. Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty/Radio Liberty. 6 June 2013. Retrieved 27 April 2015.</ref>\n\n==Tax evasion==\nIn 2015 Caball\u00e9 was under prosecution over allegations of tax evasion or fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/15/world/europe/montserrat-caballe-spanish-soprano-fails-to-appear-in-court-to-settle-tax-case.html|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9, Spanish Soprano, Fails to Appear in Court to Settle Tax Case|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194628/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/15/world/europe/montserrat-caballe-spanish-soprano-fails-to-appear-in-court-to-settle-tax-case.html|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She admitted that despite living in Spain in 2010, she had registered in [[Andorra]] in order to avoid paying [[Taxation in Spain|tax in Spain]]. In December 2015 the Spanish court found her guilty of fraud and gave her a six-month suspended jail sentence, ordering her to pay a fine of \u20ac254,231 ($280,000). She was also banned from receiving any public subsidies for a period of 18 months.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.es/20151215/spanish-soprano-montserrat-caball-gets-six-months-in-prison-for-tax-fraud Soprano Montserrat Caball\u00e9 given six month sentence for tax evasion] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216090942/http://www.thelocal.es/20151215/spanish-soprano-montserrat-caball-gets-six-months-in-prison-for-tax-fraud |date=16 December 2015 }}. ''The Local''. 15 December 2015.</ref>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9, Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed and son 1971c.jpg|thumb|Caball\u00e9 with husband and son, at [[Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II]], Milan, 1971]]\nCaball\u00e9 married Spanish tenor [[Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespanol.com/corazon/famosos/20181006/gran-historia-montserrat-caballe-marido-bernabe-marti/343465825_0.html |title=La gran historia de amor de Montserrat Caball\u00e9 y su marido Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed |first=Ane |last=Olabarrieta |date=6 October 2018 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=El Espa\u00f1ol |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006155036/https://www.elespanol.com/corazon/famosos/20181006/gran-historia-montserrat-caballe-marido-bernabe-marti/343465825_0.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They had two children; their daughter [[Montserrat Mart\u00ed]] is also an operatic soprano.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-215280 |title=Una nota de mujer |author=EFE |author-link=EFE |date=3 October 1992 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]] |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154923/https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-215280 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Health problems and death==\nOn 20 October 2012, during her tour in Russia, Caball\u00e9 suffered a [[stroke]] in [[Yekaterinburg]] and was quickly transferred to the [[Hospital de Sant Pau]] in Barcelona.<ref>{{cite news |first=Pablo |last=Mel\u00e9ndez-Haddad |title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9, en observaci\u00f3n tras sufrir un ictus reversible |url=http://www.abc.es/20121023/cultura-musica/abci-montserrat-caballe-ictus-201210231159.html |newspaper=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] |date=23 October 2012 |access-date=3 August 2014 |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715061817/http://www.abc.es/20121023/cultura-musica/abci-montserrat-caballe-ictus-201210231159.html |archive-date=15 July 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In September 2018, she was admitted to the same hospital for a gallbladder problem.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://elpais.com/ccaa/2018/09/24/catalunya/1537789003_695827.html |title=La soprano Montserrat Caball\u00e9, hospitalizada en Barcelona |location=Barcelona |date=24 September 2018 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=es |publisher=[[Prisa]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154944/https://elpais.com/ccaa/2018/09/24/catalunya/1537789003_695827.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She died there on 6 October 2018 at the age of 85. The cause of death was not given.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2018/10/06/actualidad/1538807004_654748.html |title=Muere Montserrat Caball\u00e9, la diva de todos |first=Blanca |last=Cia |date=6 October 2018 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=es |publisher=[[Prisa]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006105035/https://elpais.com/cultura/2018/10/06/actualidad/1538807004_654748.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\"/> [[Felipe VI of Spain]] described Caball\u00e9 as \"the best of the best\", and Spanish prime minister [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez (politician)|Pedro S\u00e1nchez]] called her the great ambassador of Spain.<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/spanish-opera-singer-montserrat-caballe-dies-85-n917346|title=Spanish opera singer Montserrat Caballe dies at 85|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nCaball\u00e9 recorded extensively throughout her long career and made many notable recordings of complete operas as well as recital albums. After a number of recordings early in her career for [[RCA Red Seal Records|RCA Victor Red Seal]], Caball\u00e9 also recorded for [[EMI]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], and [[Philips Records|Philips]] among other labels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/audio/?fa=subject%3Aoperas%7Ccontributor%3Acaballe%2C+montserrat&all=true |title=Audio recordings with Montserrat Caball\u00e9 |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006234757/https://www.loc.gov/audio/?fa=subject%3Aoperas%7Ccontributor%3Acaballe%2C+montserrat&all=true |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She left a \"vast discography\" of her major roles, including Aida, conducted by [[Riccardo Muti]], Elisabetta in ''Don Carlo'' conducted by [[Carlo Maria Giulini]], Fiordiligi in Mozart's ''Cos\u00ec fan tutte'' with [[Colin Davis]],<ref name=\"Gramophone\" /> Li\u00f9 in ''Turandot'' alongside Joan Sutherland and Pavarotti, conducted by [[Zubin Mehta]],<ref name=\"Steane\">{{cite web | last=Steane | first=John |url=https://www.gramophone.co.uk/feature/puccinis-turandot-a-survey-of-recordings |title=\nPuccini's Turandot: a survey of recordings |publisher=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]] |date=25 April 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2018 }}</ref> and Salome with [[Erich Leinsdorf]]. She recorded many bel canto and Rossini roles. Recital recordings include a Puccini collection with [[Charles Mackerras]], a Strauss collection with [[Leonard Bernstein]], and duets with [[Shirley Verrett]]. She performed the soprano solo in Verdi's ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]'' with [[John Barbirolli]].<ref name=\"Gramophone\" />\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Marilyn Horne: Divas in Song]]'', RCA Victor Red Seal CD, 09026-62547-2, 1994\n\n==Videography==\n* ''[[The Metropolitan Opera Centennial Gala]]'' (1983), Deutsche Grammophon DVD, 00440-073-4538, 2009\n* ''[[Glyndebourne Festival Opera: a Gala Evening]]'' (1992), Arthaus Musik DVD, 100-432, 2004\n\n==Honours and awards==\n[[File:Caballe home.jpg|thumb|Plaque at her birthplace in [[Barcelona]]]]\n[[File:M. caballe.JPG|thumb|A conservatorio in [[Arganda del Rey]] is named after her.]]\nOf Caball\u00e9's recordings, several won a [[Grammy Award]]: ''Rossini Rarities'' in 1966, Puccini's ''La boh\u00e8me'' in 1968, and Mozart's ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' in 1974; other recordings were nominated for the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/montserrat-caballe|title=Montserrat Caballe|date=22 May 2018|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n* 1966: Dame Commander of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/es/premios-principe-de-asturias/premiados/1991-victoria-de-los-angeles-teresa-berganza-montserrat-caballe-jose-carreras-pilar-lorengar-alfredo-kraus-y-placido-domingo.html| title=Premio Principe de Asturias de las Artes 1991|accessdate=31 January 2017|publisher=Fundacion Princesa de Asturias|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* 1975: Grand Cross of the [[Civil Order of Alfonso X, the Wise]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Decreto 1710/1975 por el que se concede la Gran Cruz de Orden Civil de Alfonso X El Sabio a do\u00f1a Montserrat Caball\u00e9|work=Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado|date=18 July 1975|accessdate=3 August 2014|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n y Ciencia|page=15514|language=Spanish|url=http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1975/07/18/pdfs/A15514-15514.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810043047/http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1975/07/18/pdfs/A15514-15514.pdf|archive-date=10 August 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n* 1991: [[Princess of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias for the Arts]].<ref>[https://www.elcomercio.es/culturas/musica/paso-asturias-gran-20181007010232-ntvo.html El paso por Asturias de la gran diva Montserrat Caball\u00e9] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n* 1996: {{ill|RSH-Gold|de}} in the category \"Classic LP of the Year\" (Barcelona)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsh-history.de/RSH-Gold-1996.htm|title=RSH - Wie alles begann... - RSH Gold 1996|website=Rsh-history.de|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007074025/https://www.rsh-history.de/RSH-Gold-1996.htm|archive-date=7 October 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[Bundesverdienstkreuz|Gro\u00dfes Bundesverdienstkreuz]] (Commander's Cross of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shortnews.de/id/481040/Opernstar-Montserrat-Caballe-bekommt-Bundesverdienstkreuz|title=Opernstar Montserrat Caball\u00e9 bekommt Bundesverdienstkreuz|publisher=ShortNews|date=10 October 2003|accessdate=19 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001055425/http://www.shortnews.de/id/481040/Opernstar-Montserrat-Caballe-bekommt-Bundesverdienstkreuz|archive-date=1 October 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stefanschmerbeck.de/en/mc_biographie.html|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9 \u2013 Biography|publisher=Artists Stefan Schmerbeck Management website|accessdate=19 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321143947/http://www.stefanschmerbeck.de/en/mc_biographie.html|archive-date=21 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[Legion of Honour]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elperiodicomediterraneo.com/noticias/espectaculos/caballe-recibe-legion-de-honor-de-francia_144740.html |title=Caball\u00e9 recibe la Legi\u00f3n de Honor de Francia |language=Spanish |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195050/https://www.elperiodicomediterraneo.com/noticias/espectaculos/caballe-recibe-legion-de-honor-de-francia_144740.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2007: Appointed [[Kammers\u00e4nger]]in of the [[Vienna State Opera]]<ref>[http://der-neue-merker.eu/montserrat-caballee Interview] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061125/http://der-neue-merker.eu/montserrat-caballee |date=4 March 2016 }} im ''Online Merker'', April 2007; retrieved 20 October 2015.</ref>\n* 2008: ''Honoris Causa'' doctorate from the [[Universidad Internacional Men\u00e9ndez Pelayo]] in Santander<ref>[http://www.universia.es/html_estatico/portada/actualidad/noticia_actualidad/param/noticia/jgjei.html Caball\u00e9 is conferred Honoris Causa doctorate (in Spanish)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106195527/http://www.universia.es/html_estatico/portada/actualidad/noticia_actualidad/param/noticia/jgjei.html |date=6 January 2009 }}</ref>\n* 2009: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] by the [[President of Italy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ub.edu/web/ub/galeries/documents/universitat/honoris/caballe.pdf|format=PDF|title=Universitat Honoris Caballe|website=Ub.edu|accessdate=6 October 2018|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424071541/http://www.ub.edu/web/ub/galeries/documents/universitat/honoris/caballe.pdf|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/onorificenze/insigniti/306431|title=Le onorificenze della Repubblica Italiana|trans-title=The honors of the Italian Republic|website=Quirinale.it|accessdate=6 October 2018|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195426/http://www.quirinale.it/onorificenze/insigniti/306431|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''Honoris causa'' doctorate of the [[University of Barcelona]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.avui.cat/noticia/article/5-cultura/19-cultura/367655-montserrat-caballe-investida-doctora-honoris-causa.html |title= Montserrat Caball\u00e9, investida doctora \u2018honoris causa' |accessdate= 9 February 2011 |date= 8 February 2011 |language=Catalan}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0127481|name=Montserrat Caball\u00e9}}\n* {{youtube|c2MlMkeDdVU|Montserrat Caball\u00e9: Casta Diva... Ah bello a me ritorna \u2013 Norma (1971)}}, published by [[Teatro Real]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081007044724/http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/ing/04/premiados/trayectorias/trayectoria567.html Montserrat Caball\u00e9] at [[Princess of Asturias Awards|Fundaci\u00f3n Pr\u00edncipe de Asturias]]\n* [http://www.unbeldi.com/cover.html Montserrat Caball\u00e9] unbeldi.comm\n* [http://www.weberclaudia.de/511288987313c4a03/index.html Montserrat Caball\u00e9] weberclaudia.de (in German)\n* Fiammetta Rocco: [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/when-the-ample-catalan-sings-callas-is-no-more-kiri-te-kanawa-is-making-television-commercials-but-1437682.html When the ample Catalan sings: Callas is no more; Kiri Te Kanawa is making television commercials, but Montserrat Caballe, the 61-year-old soprano with the old-fashioned style, is still the people's diva of choice] (Interview) ''[[The Independent]]'', 1994\n* [https://www.liceubarcelona.cat/ca/el-liceu-expressa-el-seu-condol-la-mort-de-montserrat-caballe El Liceu expressa el seu condol per la mort de Montserrat Caball\u00e9] (in Catalan) Liceu 6 October 2018\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/music/gallery/2018/oct/06/montserrat-caballe-a-life-in-pictures Montserrat Caball\u00e9 \u2013 a life in pictures] ''[[The Guardian]]'', 6 October 2018\n* {{YouTube|9_TKP7VHvyU|Trailer of \"Caball\u00e9 Beyond Music\", 98 min docufilm}}\n\n{{Gramophone Hall of Fame}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for the Arts}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caballe, Montserrat}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Catalan opera singers]]\n[[Category:Spanish operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Conservatori Superior de M\u00fasica del Liceu alumni]]\n[[Category:Singers from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Singers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Commanders Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:EMI Classics and Virgin Classics artists]]\n[[Category:People convicted of fraud]]\n[[Category:UNESCO Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n[[Category:Polydor Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Spanish operatic soprano}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Spanish name|Caball\u00e9|Folch}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Most Excellent|Excelent\u00edsima Se\u00f1ora]] [[Don (honorific)|Do\u00f1a]]\n| name               = Montserrat Caball\u00e9\n| alias              = La Superba\n| image              = Montserrat Caball\u00e9 1971b.jpg\n| caption            = Caball\u00e9 in [[Milan]], 1971\n| birth_name         = Mar\u00eda de Montserrat Viviana Concepci\u00f3n Caball\u00e9 i Folch\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1933|4|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Barcelona]], [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republic]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2018|10|6|1933|4|12}}\n| death_place        = Barcelona, [[Spain]]\n| education          = [[Conservatori Superior de M\u00fasica del Liceu]]\n| occupation         = Operatic [[soprano]]\n| years_active       = 1956\u20132018\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed]]|1964}}\n| children           = [[Montserrat Mart\u00ed]]<br>Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed Jr.\n| awards             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kammers\u00e4nger]]in\n* Honorary doctorate from the [[Universidad Internacional Men\u00e9ndez Pelayo]]\n* [[Princess of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award]]\n* [[Grammy Award]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mar\u00eda de Montserrat Viviana Concepci\u00f3n Caball\u00e9 i Folch''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|k|\u0259|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|l|j|e\u026a|,_|\u02cc|k|\u00e6|b|\u00e6|l|\u02c8|j|e\u026a}},<ref>{{Cite Oxford\u00a0Dictionaries|Caball\u00e9, Montserrat|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> {{IPA-ca|muns\u0259\u02c8rat k\u0259\u03b2\u0259\u02c8\u028ee i \u02c8folk|lang}}; 12 April 1933 \u2013 6 October 2018) was a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] [[operatic soprano]]. She sang a wide variety of roles, but is best known as an exponent of the works of [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]] and of the [[bel canto]] repertoire, notably the works of [[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini]], [[Vincenzo Bellini|Bellini]], and [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]]. She was noticed internationally when she stepped in for a performance of Donizetti's ''[[Lucrezia Borgia (opera)|Lucrezia Borgia]]'' at [[Carnegie Hall]] in 1965, and then appeared at leading opera houses. Her voice was described as pure but powerful, with superb control of vocal shadings and exquisite [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]].\n\nCaball\u00e9 became popular to non-classical music audiences in 1987, when she recorded, at the request of the [[International Olympic Committee|IOC]], \"[[Barcelona (Freddie Mercury and Montserrat Caball\u00e9 song)|Barcelona]]\", a duet with [[Freddie Mercury]], which became an official theme song for the [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic Games]]. She received several international awards and also [[Grammy Awards]] for a number of her recordings.\n\n==Early life and career==\nCaball\u00e9 was born in [[Barcelona]] on 12 April 1933.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Women in World History|last=Smith|first=Bonnie G.|authorlink=Bonnie G. Smith|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Her family was of humble financial circumstances due to the [[Spanish Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She studied music at the [[Liceu Conservatory]], and singing technique with Napoleone Annovazzi, Eugenia Kem\u00e9ny and [[Conchita Bad\u00eda]]. She graduated with a gold medal in 1954. She subsequently moved to [[Basel]], Switzerland, where she made her professional debut in 1956 as Mim\u00ec in Puccini's ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]''. She became part of the [[Theater Basel|Basel Opera]] company between 1957 and 1959, singing a repertoire that included Mozart (Erste Dame in ''[[The Magic Flute|Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'') and Strauss (''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'') in German, unusual for Spanish singers, but which proved useful for her next engagement at the [[Theater Bremen|Bremen Opera]] (1959\u20131962). In 1961, she starred as Iphig\u00e9nie in Gluck's ''[[Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride (Gluck)|Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride]]'' at the [[Teatro Nacional de S\u00e3o Carlos|National Theatre of S. Carlos]] in Lisbon, alongside [[Raymond Wolansky]], [[Jean Cox]], [[Paul Sch\u00f6ffler]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mt8XBGub1WsC&pg=PA308|title=The Grove Book of Operas|accessdate=6 October 2018|via=Google Books|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006155034/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mt8XBGub1WsC&pg=PA308|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, Caball\u00e9 returned to Barcelona and debuted at the [[Liceu]], singing the title role in Strauss's ''[[Arabella]]''. From the fall of 1962 through the spring of 1963 she toured Mexico, at one point singing the title role in Massenet's ''[[Manon]]'' at the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]]. This was followed by several more successful appearances at the [[Liceu]] in 1963.<ref name=\"oper\" />\n\n==Success==\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9 1969cr.jpg|thumb|Caball\u00e9 in 1969]]\nCaball\u00e9's international breakthrough came in 1965 when she replaced an indisposed [[Marilyn Horne]] in a semi-staged performance of Donizetti's ''[[Lucrezia Borgia (opera)|Lucrezia Borgia]]'' at New York's [[Carnegie Hall]], which earned her a 25-minute standing ovation. While this was her first engagement in a bel canto opera and she had to learn the role in less than one month, her performance made her famous throughout the opera world. Later that year, Caball\u00e9 made her debut at the [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera|Glyndebourne Festival]] singing her first Marschallin in Richard Strauss' ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' and portraying the role of Countess Almaviva in Mozart's ''[[The Marriage of Figaro|Le nozze di Figaro]]''.<ref name=\"oper\">[http://hosting.operissimo.com/triboni/exec?method=com.operissimo.artist.webDisplay&id=ffcyoieagxaaaaabjjco&xsl=webDisplay&searchStr= Biography of Montserrat Caball\u00e9 at operissimo.com (in German)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327202713/http://hosting.operissimo.com/triboni/exec?method=com.operissimo.artist.webDisplay&id=ffcyoieagxaaaaabjjco&xsl=webDisplay&searchStr= |date=27 March 2012 }}. Hosting.operissimo.com. Retrieved 29 October 2015.</ref>\n\nIn December 1965, she returned to Carnegie Hall for her second bel canto opera, singing the role of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]] in Donizetti's recently rediscovered ''[[Roberto Devereux]]''. Caball\u00e9 closed out the year with her [[Metropolitan Opera]] debut on 22 December 1965, appearing as Marguerite in Gounod's ''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' alongside [[John Alexander (tenor)|John Alexander]] in the title role, [[Justino D\u00edaz]] as M\u00e9phistoph\u00e9l\u00e8s, and [[Sherrill Milnes]] as Valentin in his debut at the Met.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nIn 1966, Caball\u00e9 made her first appearance with the [[Philadelphia Lyric Opera Company]] as Maddalena di Coigny in Giordano's ''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]''<ref name=\"Phili\">[[Free Library of Philadelphia]]: ''Box: Phila. Lyric Opera Company: 782.1 P5326p Bal Two [1968 \u2013 1975]''</ref> and her Italian debut at the [[Maggio Musicale Fiorentino]] as Leonora in Verdi's ''[[Il trovatore]]'', followed by Bellini's ''[[Il pirata]]'' in 1967. She returned to Philadelphia in 1967 to sing the title roles in Puccini's ''[[Tosca]]'' and ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'',<ref name=\"Phili\" /> and to the Met to sing three Verdi heroines: Leonora alongside [[Richard Tucker]] as Manrico, Desdemona in ''[[Otello]]'' with [[James McCracken]] in the title role, and Violetta in ''[[La traviata]]'', with Tucker and [[George Shirley]] alternating as Alfredo.<ref name=\"Met\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/frame.htm|title=Metropolitan Opera Association|website=Archives.metoperafamily.org|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611003537/http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/frame.htm|archive-date=11 June 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The last role in particular garnered her further acclaim among American critics and audiences.<ref name=\"oper\" /> She returned to the Met the following year in the title role in Verdi's ''[[Luisa Miller]]'', and in 1969 for the role of Li\u00f9 in Puccini's ''[[Turandot]]'', with [[Birgit Nilsson]] in the title role and [[James King (tenor)|James King]] as Cal\u00e0f.<ref name=\"Met\" /> She also returned to Philadelphia as Imogene in Bellini's ''[[Il pirata]]'' (1968) and Lucrezia Borgia (1969).<ref name=\"Phili\" />\n\nIn 1969, Caball\u00e9 appeared at the [[Arena di Verona]] in a [[Jean Vilar]] production of Verdi's ''[[Don Carlos|Don Carlo]]''. She was Elisabetta of Valois in an all-star cast including [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] and [[Piero Cappuccilli]]. Her high B on the final \"ciel\" at the end of the opera lasted more than 20 bars up to the final chord from the orchestra. In these performances she had to act on crutches because of an accident earlier that year in New York City. In the same period she also appeared in recital at the Teatro Corallo in [[Verona]]. In 1970, Caball\u00e9 made her official debut at [[La Scala]] in the title role of ''Lucrezia Borgia''. She appeared as Leonora in Philadelphia,<ref name=\"Phili\" /> and returned to the Met as Amelia in a critically acclaimed production of Verdi's ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' with Domingo as Riccardo, and [[Reri Grist]] as Oscar.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nIn 1972, she made her first appearances at [[The Royal Opera|Covent Garden]] and the [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]], both in the role of Violetta.<ref name=\"oper\" /> That same year she returned to the Met as Elisabetta in ''Don Carlo'' with [[Franco Corelli]] in the title role, and sang the title role of Bellini's ''[[Norma (opera)|Norma]]'' in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Phili\" /> In 1973 she returned to Chicago to perform the title role in Donizetti's ''[[Maria Stuarda]]'' with [[Viorica Cortez]], appeared as Violetta in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Phili\" /> She performed at the Met as Bellini's Norma, opposite [[Carlo Cossutta]] in his Met debut as Pollione and [[Fiorenza Cossotto]] as Adalgisa.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9 1975.jpg|thumb|Caball\u00e9 in 1975]]\nIn 1974, Caball\u00e9 appeared in the title role of Verdi's ''[[Aida]]'' at the Liceu in January, in Verdi's ''[[I vespri siciliani]]'' at the Met in March,<ref name=\"Met\" /> and in ''[[Parisina (opera)|Parisina d'Este]]'' at Carnegie Hall, also in March. She appeared as Norma at the [[Bolshoi Theatre]] in Moscow and in ''Adriana Lecouvreur'' at La Scala in April. She was filmed as Norma in [[Orange, Vaucluse|Orange]] in July by Pierre Jourdain. She recorded ''Aida'' with [[Riccardo Muti]] in July and made a recording of duets with [[Giuseppe Di Stefano]] in August. In September 1974, she underwent major surgery to remove a large benign mass from her abdomen. She recovered and was performing again on stage by early 1975. In 1976 Caball\u00e9 appeared at the Met once again as Norma and sang her first Aida in that house, alongside [[Robert Nagy (tenor)|Robert Nagy]] as Radam\u00e8s and Marilyn Horne as Amneris. She appeared in the title role of ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'' by Richard Strauss and sang Mim\u00ec in Puccini's ''La boh\u00e8me'' with [[Luciano Pavarotti]] as Rodolfo.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nIn 1977 Caball\u00e9 made her debut with the [[San Francisco Opera]] in the title role of Puccini's ''Turandot''. She returned to that house ten more times over the next decade in such roles as Elvira in Verdi's ''[[Ernani]]'' and the title roles in Ponchielli's ''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'', Rossini's ''[[Semiramide]]'', and Puccini's ''Tosca'', among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007224557/http://archive.sfopera.com/qry3WebCastlist.asp?psearchall=on&psearch=Montserrat%20Caball%C3%A9&psearchtype |title=San Francisco Opera Performance Archive |website=Web.archive.org |date=2018-10-07 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nHaving lost some of her earlier brilliance and purity of voice, Caball\u00e9 offered more dramatic expressive singing in roles that demanded it. In 1978, she was Tosca in San Francisco with Pavarotti, Norma in Madrid, and Adriana Lecouvreur at the Met opposite [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]]. She continued to appear often at the Met during the 1980s, in roles such as Tosca (1980, 1985) and Elisabetta (1985), and also sang concerts in 1981 and 1983. Her final performance at the Met was on 10 October 1985 in ''Tosca'' with Pavarotti as Cavaradossi and [[Cornell MacNeil]] as Scarpia.<ref name=\"Met\" />\n\nHer voice was noted for its purity, precise control, and power. She was admired less for her dramatic instincts and acting skills than for her superb technique, vocal shadings, and exquisite [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]]s, which were inspired by [[Miguel Fleta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/03/09/134141700/montserrat-caball-a-voice-of-passionate-grandeur/|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9: A Voice of Passionate Grandeur|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154817/https://www.npr.org/2011/03/09/134141700/montserrat-caball-a-voice-of-passionate-grandeur/|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diarci.com/2012/10/12/perfectly-lovely-montserrat-caballe/|title=Perfectly Lovely \u2013 Montserrat Caballe|date=13 October 2012|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154759/http://www.diarci.com/2012/10/12/perfectly-lovely-montserrat-caballe/|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voiceteacher.com/cuperto.html|title=The Cuperto|website=voiceteacher.com|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206230329/http://www.voiceteacher.com/cuperto.html|archive-date=6 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://voiceandopera.blogspot.com/2011/08/those-caballe-pianissimi.html|title=Voice and opera training: Those Caballe pianissimi|first=Joel|last=Katz|date=4 August 2011|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006114731/http://voiceandopera.blogspot.com/2011/08/those-caballe-pianissimi.html|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Assoluta Voice in Opera, 1797\u20131847|last=Riggs|first=Geoffrey S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GhXggJliLF8C|publisher=McFarland|year=2003|isbn=0786440775|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|pages=125, 127, 144|access-date=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006234813/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GhXggJliLF8C|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nIn Bellini's ''Norma'', Caball\u00e9 recorded both the title role (for [[RCA Red Seal Records|RCA Red Seal]] in 1972, with Domingo as Pollione) and later the role of Adalgisa, to [[Joan Sutherland]]'s Norma in a 1984 [[Decca Records|Decca]] recording conducted by [[Richard Bonynge]]. Although Bellini conceived the role of Adalgisa originally for a soprano, it is usually now sung by a [[mezzo-soprano]]. Caball\u00e9 was one of few sopranos to have recorded the role, although she was over 50 years old at the time of the recording in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w0qMf-bAx_QC&pg=PA11|title=Opera for Libraries: A Guide to Core Works, Audio and Video Recordings, Books and Serials|first=Clyde T.|last=McCants|date=28 February 2003|publisher=McFarland|accessdate=6 October 2018|via=Google Books|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006155047/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w0qMf-bAx_QC&pg=PA11|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1986 she also took a role in the biographic film ''[[Romanza final]]'', directed by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Forqu\u00e9]].\n\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9.jpg|thumb|left|upright|As Rossini's [[Semiramide]] at the 1980 [[Aix-en-Provence Festival]]]]\nIn 1987, Caball\u00e9 made a rare excursion into the world of pop music when she released a duet with [[Freddie Mercury]], the lead singer of the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], which was titled \"[[Barcelona (Freddie Mercury and Montserrat Caball\u00e9 song)|Barcelona]]\".<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9, Barcelona opera singer, dies at 85 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-45769808 |accessdate=6 October 2018 |publisher=BBC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006080359/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-45769808 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The song was inspired by Caball\u00e9's home city and later used as one of the two official theme songs for the [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"BBC\" /> Mercury was a great admirer of Caball\u00e9, considering her voice to be \"the best in the world\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/sep/27/freddie-mercury-great-enigma | title=Freddie Mercury: the great enigma | work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London | first=Caroline | last=Sullivan | date=27 September 2012 | accessdate=9 April 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609093810/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/sep/27/freddie-mercury-great-enigma | archive-date=9 June 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The single was followed by an [[Barcelona (Freddie Mercury and Montserrat Caball\u00e9 album)|album of the same name]] which was released the following year and featured further collaborations between the two performers. The title track later became the anthem of the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] which was hosted by Caball\u00e9's native city, and appeared again in the pop music charts throughout Europe. Caball\u00e9 also performed the song live, accompanied by a recording by Mercury, who had died in 1991, before the 1999 [[UEFA Champions League]] football final in Barcelona's [[Camp Nou]] stadium.<ref>{{cite journal |year=1999 |editor1-last=Mitten |editor1-first=Andy |title=The Long Road Trip to Victory |journal=Kings of Europe |publisher=Manchester United |page=11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pilger |first1=Sam |date=June 1999 |editor1-last=Barnes |editor1-first=Justyn |title=The Promised Land |journal=Manchester United |publisher=Manchester United |volume=7 |issue=8 |page=27 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, writing for ''[[The Independent]]'', Fiammetta Rocco said: \"Caballe is one of the last of the true divas. Callas is dead, [[Kiri Te Kanawa]] is busy making commercials for [[Sainsbury's]], and [[Mirella Freni]] has never really risen out of the narrow confines of being an opera lover's opera-singer. Caballe, on the other hand, has always had an enormous following, and it's still with her today.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/when-the-ample-catalan-sings-callas-is-no-more-kiri-te-kanawa-is-making-television-commercials-but-1437682.html|title=When the ample Catalan sings: Callas is no more; Kiri Te Kanawa is|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154930/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/when-the-ample-catalan-sings-callas-is-no-more-kiri-te-kanawa-is-making-television-commercials-but-1437682.html|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995 she worked with [[Vangelis]] for his album ''[[El Greco (album)|El Greco]]'', dedicated to [[El Greco|the Greek painter]].  In 1997, [[Mike Moran (music producer)|Mike Moran]] produced the album ''[[Friends for Life (Montserrat Caball\u00e9 album)|Friends For Life]]'', which includes duets with Caball\u00e9 and such singers as [[Bruce Dickinson]], [[Johnny Hallyday]], [[Johnny Logan (singer)|Johnny Logan]], [[Gino Vannelli]], and [[Helmut Lotti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/montserrat-caball%C3%A9-friends-for-life-mw0000451837/credits|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9: Friends for Life \u2013 Montserrat Caball\u00e9 \u2013 Credits|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194723/https://www.allmusic.com/album/montserrat-caball%C3%A9-friends-for-life-mw0000451837/credits|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCaball\u00e9 dedicated herself to various charities. She was a [[UNESCO Goodwill Ambassador]] and established a foundation for needy children in Barcelona. In 2003, she starred in her own documentary film ''Caball\u00e9: Beyond Music'', which featured many well-known opera singers, including Domingo, Pavarotti, Carreras, and [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operatoday.com/content/2005/04/caballe_beyond_.php |title=Caballe: Beyond Music |website=operatoday:com |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194622/http://www.operatoday.com/content/2005/04/caballe_beyond_.php |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, she appeared as Catherine of Aragon in ''[[Henry VIII (opera)|Henri VIII]]'' by Saint-Sa\u00ebns, and in 2004 in the title role of Massenet's ''[[Cl\u00e9op\u00e2tre]]'', both at the Liceu. She appeared as The Duchess of Crakenthorp in Donizetti's ''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' at the [[Vienna State Opera]] in April 2007.<ref name=\"Vienna\">{{cite web |url=https://archiv.wiener-staatsoper.at/search/person/455 |title=Vorstellungen mit Montserrat Caball\u00e9 |publisher=[[Vienna State Opera]] |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194739/https://archiv.wiener-staatsoper.at/search/person/455 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Patrick O'Connor wrote in ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'' that{{quote|no diva in memory has sung such an all-encompassing amount of the soprano repertory, progressing through virtually the entire range of Italian light lyric, [[Spinto|lirico-spinto]] and dramatic roles, including all the pinnacles of the bel canto, Verdi and verismo repertories, whilst simultaneously being a remarkable interpreter of Salome, Sieglinde and Isolde.<ref name=\"Gramophone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gramophone.co.uk/classical-music-news/the-soprano-montserrat-caball%C3%A9-has-died |title=The soprano Montserrat Caball\u00e9 has died |publisher=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]] |date=6 October 2018 |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006162041/https://www.gramophone.co.uk/classical-music-news/the-soprano-montserrat-caball%C3%A9-has-died |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nOn 6 June 2013, Caball\u00e9 was declared [[List of people declared personae non gratae in Azerbaijan|''persona non grata'' in Azerbaijan]] after visiting, despite official warnings issued by the Azerbaijani embassy in Spain, the de facto independent state [[Nagorno-Karabakh]] and meeting with local leaders.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/azerbaijan-montserrat-caballe/25009201.html Montserrat Caballe Declared Persona Non Grata In Azerbaijan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107083917/http://www.rferl.org/content/azerbaijan-montserrat-caballe/25009201.html |date=7 January 2016 }}. Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty/Radio Liberty. 6 June 2013. Retrieved 27 April 2015.</ref>\n\n==Tax evasion==\nIn 2015 Caball\u00e9 was under prosecution over allegations of tax evasion or fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/15/world/europe/montserrat-caballe-spanish-soprano-fails-to-appear-in-court-to-settle-tax-case.html|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9, Spanish Soprano, Fails to Appear in Court to Settle Tax Case|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006194628/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/15/world/europe/montserrat-caballe-spanish-soprano-fails-to-appear-in-court-to-settle-tax-case.html|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She admitted that despite living in Spain in 2010, she had registered in [[Andorra]] in order to avoid paying [[Taxation in Spain|tax in Spain]]. In December 2015 the Spanish court found her guilty of fraud and gave her a six-month suspended jail sentence, ordering her to pay a fine of \u20ac254,231 ($280,000). She was also banned from receiving any public subsidies for a period of 18 months.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.es/20151215/spanish-soprano-montserrat-caball-gets-six-months-in-prison-for-tax-fraud Soprano Montserrat Caball\u00e9 given six month sentence for tax evasion] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216090942/http://www.thelocal.es/20151215/spanish-soprano-montserrat-caball-gets-six-months-in-prison-for-tax-fraud |date=16 December 2015 }}. ''The Local''. 15 December 2015.</ref>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Montserrat Caball\u00e9, Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed and son 1971c.jpg|thumb|Caball\u00e9 with husband and son, at [[Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II]], Milan, 1971]]\nCaball\u00e9 married Spanish tenor [[Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespanol.com/corazon/famosos/20181006/gran-historia-montserrat-caballe-marido-bernabe-marti/343465825_0.html |title=La gran historia de amor de Montserrat Caball\u00e9 y su marido Bernab\u00e9 Mart\u00ed |first=Ane |last=Olabarrieta |date=6 October 2018 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=El Espa\u00f1ol |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006155036/https://www.elespanol.com/corazon/famosos/20181006/gran-historia-montserrat-caballe-marido-bernabe-marti/343465825_0.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They had two children; their daughter [[Montserrat Mart\u00ed]] is also an operatic soprano.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-215280 |title=Una nota de mujer |author=EFE |author-link=EFE |date=3 October 1992 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]] |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154923/https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-215280 |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Health problems and death==\nOn 20 October 2012, during her tour in Russia, Caball\u00e9 suffered a [[stroke]] in [[Yekaterinburg]] and was quickly transferred to the [[Hospital de Sant Pau]] in Barcelona.<ref>{{cite news |first=Pablo |last=Mel\u00e9ndez-Haddad |title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9, en observaci\u00f3n tras sufrir un ictus reversible |url=http://www.abc.es/20121023/cultura-musica/abci-montserrat-caballe-ictus-201210231159.html |newspaper=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] |date=23 October 2012 |access-date=3 August 2014 |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715061817/http://www.abc.es/20121023/cultura-musica/abci-montserrat-caballe-ictus-201210231159.html |archive-date=15 July 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In September 2018, she was admitted to the same hospital for a gallbladder problem.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://elpais.com/ccaa/2018/09/24/catalunya/1537789003_695827.html |title=La soprano Montserrat Caball\u00e9, hospitalizada en Barcelona |location=Barcelona |date=24 September 2018 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=es |publisher=[[Prisa]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006154944/https://elpais.com/ccaa/2018/09/24/catalunya/1537789003_695827.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She died there on 6 October 2018 at the age of 85. The cause of death was not given.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2018/10/06/actualidad/1538807004_654748.html |title=Muere Montserrat Caball\u00e9, la diva de todos |first=Blanca |last=Cia |date=6 October 2018 |access-date=6 October 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=es |publisher=[[Prisa]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006105035/https://elpais.com/cultura/2018/10/06/actualidad/1538807004_654748.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\"/> [[Felipe VI of Spain]] described Caball\u00e9 as \"the best of the best\", and Spanish prime minister [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez (politician)|Pedro S\u00e1nchez]] called her the great ambassador of Spain.<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/spanish-opera-singer-montserrat-caballe-dies-85-n917346|title=Spanish opera singer Montserrat Caballe dies at 85|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nCaball\u00e9 recorded extensively throughout her long career and made many notable recordings of complete operas as well as recital albums. After a number of recordings early in her career for [[RCA Red Seal Records|RCA Victor Red Seal]], Caball\u00e9 also recorded for [[EMI]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], and [[Philips Records|Philips]] among other labels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/audio/?fa=subject%3Aoperas%7Ccontributor%3Acaballe%2C+montserrat&all=true |title=Audio recordings with Montserrat Caball\u00e9 |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006234757/https://www.loc.gov/audio/?fa=subject%3Aoperas%7Ccontributor%3Acaballe%2C+montserrat&all=true |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She left a \"vast discography\" of her major roles, including Aida, conducted by [[Riccardo Muti]], Elisabetta in ''Don Carlo'' conducted by [[Carlo Maria Giulini]], Fiordiligi in Mozart's ''Cos\u00ec fan tutte'' with [[Colin Davis]],<ref name=\"Gramophone\" /> Li\u00f9 in ''Turandot'' alongside Joan Sutherland and Pavarotti, conducted by [[Zubin Mehta]],<ref name=\"Steane\">{{cite web | last=Steane | first=John |url=https://www.gramophone.co.uk/feature/puccinis-turandot-a-survey-of-recordings |title=\nPuccini's Turandot: a survey of recordings |publisher=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]] |date=25 April 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2018 }}</ref> and Salome with [[Erich Leinsdorf]]. She recorded many bel canto and Rossini roles. Recital recordings include a Puccini collection with [[Charles Mackerras]], a Strauss collection with [[Leonard Bernstein]], and duets with [[Shirley Verrett]]. She performed the soprano solo in Verdi's ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]'' with [[John Barbirolli]].<ref name=\"Gramophone\" />\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Marilyn Horne: Divas in Song]]'', RCA Victor Red Seal CD, 09026-62547-2, 1994\n\n==Videography==\n* ''[[The Metropolitan Opera Centennial Gala]]'' (1983), Deutsche Grammophon DVD, 00440-073-4538, 2009\n* ''[[Glyndebourne Festival Opera: a Gala Evening]]'' (1992), Arthaus Musik DVD, 100-432, 2004\n\n==Honours and awards==\n[[File:Caballe home.jpg|thumb|Plaque at her birthplace in [[Barcelona]]]]\n[[File:M. caballe.JPG|thumb|A conservatorio in [[Arganda del Rey]] is named after her.]]\nOf Caball\u00e9's recordings, several won a [[Grammy Award]]: ''Rossini Rarities'' in 1966, Puccini's ''La boh\u00e8me'' in 1968, and Mozart's ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' in 1974; other recordings were nominated for the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/montserrat-caballe|title=Montserrat Caballe|date=22 May 2018|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n* 1966: Dame Commander of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/es/premios-principe-de-asturias/premiados/1991-victoria-de-los-angeles-teresa-berganza-montserrat-caballe-jose-carreras-pilar-lorengar-alfredo-kraus-y-placido-domingo.html| title=Premio Principe de Asturias de las Artes 1991|accessdate=31 January 2017|publisher=Fundacion Princesa de Asturias|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* 1975: Grand Cross of the [[Civil Order of Alfonso X, the Wise]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Decreto 1710/1975 por el que se concede la Gran Cruz de Orden Civil de Alfonso X El Sabio a do\u00f1a Montserrat Caball\u00e9|work=Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado|date=18 July 1975|accessdate=3 August 2014|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n y Ciencia|page=15514|language=Spanish|url=http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1975/07/18/pdfs/A15514-15514.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810043047/http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1975/07/18/pdfs/A15514-15514.pdf|archive-date=10 August 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n* 1991: [[Princess of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias for the Arts]].<ref>[https://www.elcomercio.es/culturas/musica/paso-asturias-gran-20181007010232-ntvo.html El paso por Asturias de la gran diva Montserrat Caball\u00e9] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n* 1996: {{ill|RSH-Gold|de}} in the category \"Classic LP of the Year\" (Barcelona)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsh-history.de/RSH-Gold-1996.htm|title=RSH - Wie alles begann... - RSH Gold 1996|website=Rsh-history.de|accessdate=6 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007074025/https://www.rsh-history.de/RSH-Gold-1996.htm|archive-date=7 October 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[Bundesverdienstkreuz|Gro\u00dfes Bundesverdienstkreuz]] (Commander's Cross of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shortnews.de/id/481040/Opernstar-Montserrat-Caballe-bekommt-Bundesverdienstkreuz|title=Opernstar Montserrat Caball\u00e9 bekommt Bundesverdienstkreuz|publisher=ShortNews|date=10 October 2003|accessdate=19 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001055425/http://www.shortnews.de/id/481040/Opernstar-Montserrat-Caballe-bekommt-Bundesverdienstkreuz|archive-date=1 October 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stefanschmerbeck.de/en/mc_biographie.html|title=Montserrat Caball\u00e9 \u2013 Biography|publisher=Artists Stefan Schmerbeck Management website|accessdate=19 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321143947/http://www.stefanschmerbeck.de/en/mc_biographie.html|archive-date=21 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[Legion of Honour]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elperiodicomediterraneo.com/noticias/espectaculos/caballe-recibe-legion-de-honor-de-francia_144740.html |title=Caball\u00e9 recibe la Legi\u00f3n de Honor de Francia |language=Spanish |accessdate=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195050/https://www.elperiodicomediterraneo.com/noticias/espectaculos/caballe-recibe-legion-de-honor-de-francia_144740.html |archive-date=6 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2007: Appointed [[Kammers\u00e4nger]]in of the [[Vienna State Opera]]<ref>[http://der-neue-merker.eu/montserrat-caballee Interview] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061125/http://der-neue-merker.eu/montserrat-caballee |date=4 March 2016 }} im ''Online Merker'', April 2007; retrieved 20 October 2015.</ref>\n* 2008: ''Honoris Causa'' doctorate from the [[Universidad Internacional Men\u00e9ndez Pelayo]] in Santander<ref>[http://www.universia.es/html_estatico/portada/actualidad/noticia_actualidad/param/noticia/jgjei.html Caball\u00e9 is conferred Honoris Causa doctorate (in Spanish)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106195527/http://www.universia.es/html_estatico/portada/actualidad/noticia_actualidad/param/noticia/jgjei.html |date=6 January 2009 }}</ref>\n* 2009: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] by the [[President of Italy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ub.edu/web/ub/galeries/documents/universitat/honoris/caballe.pdf|format=PDF|title=Universitat Honoris Caballe|website=Ub.edu|accessdate=6 October 2018|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424071541/http://www.ub.edu/web/ub/galeries/documents/universitat/honoris/caballe.pdf|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/onorificenze/insigniti/306431|title=Le onorificenze della Repubblica Italiana|trans-title=The honors of the Italian Republic|website=Quirinale.it|accessdate=6 October 2018|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195426/http://www.quirinale.it/onorificenze/insigniti/306431|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''Honoris causa'' doctorate of the [[University of Barcelona]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.avui.cat/noticia/article/5-cultura/19-cultura/367655-montserrat-caballe-investida-doctora-honoris-causa.html |title= Montserrat Caball\u00e9, investida doctora \u2018honoris causa' |accessdate= 9 February 2011 |date= 8 February 2011 |language=Catalan}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0127481|name=Montserrat Caball\u00e9}}\n* {{youtube|c2MlMkeDdVU|Montserrat Caball\u00e9: Casta Diva... Ah bello a me ritorna \u2013 Norma (1971)}}, published by [[Teatro Real]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081007044724/http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/ing/04/premiados/trayectorias/trayectoria567.html Montserrat Caball\u00e9] at [[Princess of Asturias Awards|Fundaci\u00f3n Pr\u00edncipe de Asturias]]\n* [http://www.unbeldi.com/cover.html Montserrat Caball\u00e9] unbeldi.comm\n* [http://www.weberclaudia.de/511288987313c4a03/index.html Montserrat Caball\u00e9] weberclaudia.de (in German)\n* Fiammetta Rocco: [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/when-the-ample-catalan-sings-callas-is-no-more-kiri-te-kanawa-is-making-television-commercials-but-1437682.html When the ample Catalan sings: Callas is no more; Kiri Te Kanawa is making television commercials, but Montserrat Caballe, the 61-year-old soprano with the old-fashioned style, is still the people's diva of choice] (Interview) ''[[The Independent]]'', 1994\n* [https://www.liceubarcelona.cat/ca/el-liceu-expressa-el-seu-condol-la-mort-de-montserrat-caballe El Liceu expressa el seu condol per la mort de Montserrat Caball\u00e9] (in Catalan) Liceu 6 October 2018\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/music/gallery/2018/oct/06/montserrat-caballe-a-life-in-pictures Montserrat Caball\u00e9 \u2013 a life in pictures] ''[[The Guardian]]'', 6 October 2018\n* {{YouTube|9_TKP7VHvyU|Trailer of \"Caball\u00e9 Beyond Music\", 98 min docufilm}}\n\n{{Gramophone Hall of Fame}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for the Arts}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caballe, Montserrat}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Catalan opera singers]]\n[[Category:Spanish operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Conservatori Superior de M\u00fasica del 